        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          A statistical comparison to highlight what I mean about the aggregate scoreline not being indicative of the difference in the teams' respective abilities. If you take chances created and convert so that Barcelona end up with the number of goals they scored, you get an aggregate of 5 - 3.333 in their favour (or 5-3 when converting to a whole number obviously). That's essentially the difference I see over 180 minutes of football, a 2 goal difference- albeit it was without our best CM, somebody who was immense against the best midfield in the world- Bayern Munich's "VAT" and our 2 other best players in a run of poor form. Speculation to how we would've faired with Santi in the team and Mesut & Alexis on form, my guess is we would've created more but still missed at the same ratio as I've seen all season. Essentially, we need a world class finisher and that's the biggest difference between the 2 sides. Amazing when you consider Barca have 3 up front!

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          I was proud with our performance tonight. We lost but we deserved a draw. Over the 2 legs, Barcelona were better so deserve to go through. I can't argue the result of the tie but the scoreline doesn't do us justice imo. In terms of chance creating, both teams were level and if we had their front 3, we would've won by a couple of goals ourselves. I don't agree when people say quality of individuals decided the first leg, I thought a large part of that was down to poor 2nd half tactics and timidness but this game pretty much was 50-50 with world class strikers deciding the result. We dilly-dallied with our chances (although the fact Welbeck got in those positions is a positive for his development into a 9 is concerned) which allowed the Barca defence to get back whereas Neymar and Messi shot at the exactly the right time. Can't defend against Suarez's volley and it's the 3rd time in as many weeks a wonder goal has been the decisive one. All the fans want to see is effort and we got that.

        • [ - ] SteveHyland - member since 03-Nov-12

          @Quest- I do get what you mean by the section of your comment- "...one who knows both teams well could easily see that Barcelona would trump as they did" but I simply don't agree. In my experience of watching even good teams of the past (and Arsenal are a good team, not just a great one) it's the creation of chances, or more importantly, a lack of, which gives the air of predictability of a result. I would wage 8 weeks of YOUR money lol, that no team has created as many chances as Arsenal did at the Nou Camp and Real Madrid definitely wont on the 2nd April. Sure we didn't convert them, and we're bottom of the prem in terms of conversion, but ultimately I don't see a team that contains good players and a couple of world class ones that happens to create a ton of chances as predictable losers. We wouldn't have been able to beat Bayern if it was that clear cut. Neymar and Suarez actually converted their chances at a BETTER ratio than their season avgs incidentally and needed to to win.
